00:30:04.719 --> 00:30:07.330
AUDIENCE: Yeah, it's
roughly 500 [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:07.330 --> 00:30:09.570
CATHERINE DRENNAN:
OK, 26, and so

00:30:09.570 --> 00:30:11.650
what does this come out to be?

00:30:11.650 --> 00:30:14.150
{}

00:30:14.150 --> 00:30:17.470
AUDIENCE: 0.050.

00:30:17.470 --> 00:30:22.420
CATHERINE DRENNAN: 0.050, And
now we need to plug that in.

00:30:22.420 --> 00:30:37.560
So we have d equals the square
root of 0.050 times 12.14.

00:30:37.560 --> 00:30:39.246
And what does that
come out to be?

00:30:45.910 --> 00:31:00.240
2.71-- and the actual was 2.5.

00:31:00.240 --> 00:31:00.740
Not bad.

00:31:05.070 --> 00:31:08.700
So using methods
very similar to this,

00:31:08.700 --> 00:31:10.830
Rutherford was
able to figure out

00:31:10.830 --> 00:31:14.130
what the diameter
of the nucleus was.

00:31:14.130 --> 00:31:20.280
And this was a really important
achievement of the time.

00:31:20.280 --> 00:31:29.790
OK, so in the last few minutes,
maybe I'll move this down.

00:31:29.790 --> 00:31:31.750
In the last few
minutes, I want to talk

00:31:31.750 --> 00:31:35.620
about the fall out of all
of these great experiments

00:31:35.620 --> 00:31:37.730
and all of these great results.

00:31:37.730 --> 00:31:42.590
So we now know there is
an electron and a nucleus.

00:31:42.590 --> 00:31:44.920
So there are
subatomic particles.

00:31:44.920 --> 00:31:47.530
What does that mean in terms
of what people thought they

00:31:47.530 --> 00:31:50.325
understood about atomic theory?

00:31:53.850 --> 00:31:56.660
So we had this question then.

00:31:56.660 --> 00:32:00.940
OK, so we have a nucleus,
positively charged,

00:32:00.940 --> 00:32:02.540
and electron,
negatively charged.

00:32:02.540 --> 00:32:05.010
And there's a
distance between them.

00:32:05.010 --> 00:32:11.550
And wanted to know,
why do they stay apart?

00:32:11.550 --> 00:32:16.000
Why does the electron not
crash into the nucleus?

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:19.210
So from classical
description, we

00:32:19.210 --> 00:32:22.990
have Coulomb's Force
Law, which tells us

00:32:22.990 --> 00:32:26.950
about the force
when you have two

00:32:26.950 --> 00:32:33.280
charged particles, Q1 and Q2,
so the charge on the particles.

00:32:33.280 --> 00:32:38.230
And you have over
4 times pi times

00:32:38.230 --> 00:32:43.900
this permittivity constant
times the distance, r, squared.

00:32:43.900 --> 00:32:49.990
So if you apply a force then,
and you have charged particles,

00:32:49.990 --> 00:32:53.180
if those particles
have the same sign,

00:32:53.180 --> 00:32:56.200
then acceleration
should push them apart.

00:32:56.200 --> 00:32:59.170
The force should be
positive and repulsive.

00:32:59.170 --> 00:33:02.020
So two things with
the same charge

00:33:02.020 --> 00:33:03.730
don't want to be
near each other.

00:33:03.730 --> 00:33:06.190
It's going to be repulsive.

00:33:06.190 --> 00:33:09.190
If, like in this case,
you have two things

00:33:09.190 --> 00:33:12.520
that have opposite
signs, acceleration

00:33:12.520 --> 00:33:15.520
should pull them together.

00:33:15.520 --> 00:33:20.110
And here the force should
be negative and attractive.

00:33:20.110 --> 00:33:22.240
So that's the situation
we're in here,

00:33:22.240 --> 00:33:28.000
positively charged nucleus,
negatively charged electron.

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:32.866
So let's consider
then a hydrogen atom.

00:33:32.866 --> 00:33:38.290
It equals one
electron, one proton.

00:33:38.290 --> 00:33:41.620
Let's think about
what happens when

00:33:41.620 --> 00:33:46.220
